msgid "Every listed shell supports an internal timeout shell variable that can be set to a specific time value to cause the inactivity timeout. If you want to prevent users from overriding the timeout setting, you can mark the corresponding shell timeout variable as read-only. The corresponding variable declaration syntax is also found in the table above."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: user_management.xml:651
#, no-c-format
msgid "No protection from hostile users"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: user_management.xml:652
#, no-c-format
msgid "This feature is only helpful for avoiding risks if a user is forgetful or follows unsafe practices. It does not protect against hostile users. The timeout only applies to interactive wait states of a shell. A malicious user can always find ways to circumvent the timeout and keep their session open regardless."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: user_management.xml:660
#, no-c-format
msgid "To configure the inactivity timeout, you need to add the matching timeout variable declaration to each shell's start-up script. Use either the path for login shells only, or the one for all shells, as listed in the table. The following example uses paths and settings that are suitable for <command>bash</command> and <command>ksh</command> to set up a read-only login shell timeout that cannot be overridden by users. Create the file <filename>/etc/profile.d/timeout.sh</filename> with the following content:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: user_management.xml:670
#, no-c-format
msgid "# /etc/profile.d/timeout.sh for SUSE Linux\n"
      "#\n"
      "# Timeout in seconds until the bash/ksh session is terminated\n"
      "# in case of inactivity.\n"
      "# 24h = 86400 sec\n"
      "readonly TMOUT=86400"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: user_management.xml:678
#, no-c-format
msgid "We recommend using the <command>screen</command> tool to detach sessions before logging out. <command>screen</command> sessions are not terminated and can be re-attached whenever required. An active session can be locked without logging out (read about <keycombo> <keycombo><keycap function=\"control\"/><keycap>A</keycap></keycombo> <keycap>X</keycap></keycombo> / <command>lockscreen</command> in <command>man screen</command> for details)."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: user_management.xml:691
#, no-c-format
msgid "Preventing accidental denial of service"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: user_management.xml:693
#, no-c-format
msgid "Linux allows you to set limits on the amount of system resources that users and groups can consume. This is also useful if bugs in programs cause them to use up too many resources (for example, memory leaks), slow down the machine, or even render the system unusable. Incorrect settings can allow programs to use too many resources, which might make the server unresponsive to new connections or even local logins (for example, if a program uses up all available file handles on the host). This can also be a security concern if someone is allowed to consume all system resources and therefore cause a denial-of-service attack&mdash;either unplanned, or worse, planned. Setting resource limits for users and groups might be an effective way to protect systems, depending on the environment."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: user_management.xml:708
#, no-c-format
msgid "Example for restricting system resources"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: user_management.xml:709
#, no-c-format
msgid "The following example demonstrates the practical usage of setting or restricting system resource consumption for an Oracle user account. For a list of system resource settings, see <filename>/etc/security/limits.conf</filename> or <command>man limits.conf</command> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: user_management.xml:716
#, no-c-format
msgid "Most shells, such as Bash, provide control over various resources (for example, the maximum allowable number of open file descriptors or the maximum number of processes) that are available on a per-user basis. To examine all current limits in the shell, execute:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: user_management.xml:722
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.root;ulimit -a"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: user_management.xml:723
#, no-c-format
msgid "For more information on <command>ulimit</command> for the Bash shell, examine the Bash man pages."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: user_management.xml:728
#, no-c-format
msgid "Setting limits for SSH sessions"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: user_management.xml:729
#, no-c-format
msgid "Setting <quote>hard</quote> and <quote>soft</quote> limits might not have the expected results when using an SSH session. To see valid behavior, it might be necessary to log in as root, and then <command>su</command> to the ID with limits (for example, <literal>Oracle</literal> in these examples). Resource limits should also work assuming the application was started automatically during the boot process. It might be necessary to set <option>UsePrivilegeSeparation</option> in <filename>/etc/ssh/sshd_config</filename> to <literal>no</literal> and restart the SSH daemon ( <command>systemctl restart sshd</command> ) if it seems that the changes to resource limits are not working (via SSH). However, this is not generally recommended, as it weakens a system's security."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: user_management.xml:745
#, no-c-format
msgid "Disabling password logins via <command>ssh</command>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: user_management.xml:746
#, no-c-format
msgid "You can add extra security to your server by disabling password authentication for SSH. Remember that you need to have SSH keys configured, otherwise you cannot access the server. To disable password login, add the following lines to <filename>/etc/ssh/sshd_config</filename> :"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: user_management.xml:753
#, no-c-format
msgid "UseLogin no\n"
      "UsePAM no\n"
      "PasswordAuthentication no\n"
      "PubkeyAuthentication yes"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: user_management.xml:758
#, no-c-format
msgid "In this example, a change to the number of file handles or open files that the user <literal>oracle</literal> can use is made by editing <filename>/etc/security/limits.conf</filename> as &rootuser; making the following changes:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: user_management.xml:764
#, no-c-format
msgid "oracle           soft    nofile          4096\n"
      "oracle           hard    nofile          63536"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: user_management.xml:766
#, no-c-format
msgid "The soft limit in the first line defines the limit on the number of file handles (open files) that the <systemitem class=\"username\">oracle</systemitem> user has after login. If the user sees error messages about running out of file handles, then the user can increase the number of file handles like in this example up to the hard limit (in this example 63536) by executing:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: user_management.xml:774
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.root;ulimit -n 63536"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: user_management.xml:775
#, no-c-format
msgid "You can set the soft and hard limits higher if necessary."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: user_management.xml:779
#, no-c-format
msgid "Caution with using ulimits"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: user_management.xml:780
#, no-c-format
msgid "It is important to be judicious with the usage of ulimits. Allowing a <quote>hard</quote> limit for <literal>nofile</literal> for a user that is equal to the kernel limit ( <filename>/proc/sys/fs/file-max</filename> ) is bad. If the user consumes all the available file handles, the system cannot initiate new logins, since it is not possible to access the PAM modules required to perform a login."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: user_management.xml:789
#, no-c-format
msgid "You also need to ensure that <literal>pam_limits</literal> is either configured globally in <filename>/etc/pam.d/common-auth</filename> , or for individual services like SSH, su, login and telnet in:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: member
#: user_management.xml:795
#, no-c-format
msgid "<filename>/etc/pam.d/sshd</filename> (for SSH)"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: member
#: user_management.xml:796
#, no-c-format
msgid "<filename>/etc/pam.d/su</filename> (for su)"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: member
#: user_management.xml:797
#, no-c-format
msgid "<filename>/etc/pam.d/login</filename> (local logins and telnet)"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: user_management.xml:799
#, no-c-format
msgid "If you do not want to enable it for all logins, there is a specific PAM module that reads the <filename>/etc/security/limits.conf</filename> file. Entries in PAM configuration directives have entries like:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: user_management.xml:804
#, no-c-format
msgid "session     required      /lib/security/pam_limits.so\n"
      "session     required      /lib/security/pam_unix.so"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: user_management.xml:806
#, no-c-format
msgid "Changes are not immediate and require a new login session:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: user_management.xml:810
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.root;su - oracle\n"
      "&prompt.user;ulimit -n\n"
      "4096"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: user_management.xml:813
#, no-c-format
msgid "These examples are specific to the Bash shell; <command>ulimit</command> options are different for other shells. The default limit for the user <literal>oracle</literal> is <literal>4096</literal> . To increase the number of file handles the user <literal>oracle</literal> can use to <literal>63536</literal> , execute:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: user_management.xml:820
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.root;su - oracle\n"
      "&prompt.user;ulimit -n\n"
      "4096\n"
      "&prompt.user;ulimit -n 63536\n"
      "&prompt.user;ulimit -n\n"
      "63536"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: user_management.xml:826
#, no-c-format
msgid "Making this permanent requires the addition of the setting, <command>ulimit -n 63536</command> , (again, for Bash) to the user's profile ( <filename>~/.bashrc</filename> or <filename>~/.profile</filename> file), which is the user start-up file for the Bash shell on &productname; (to verify your shell, run: <command>echo $SHELL</command> ). To do this you could run the following commands for the Bash shell of the user <literal>oracle</literal> :"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: user_management.xml:835
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.root;su - oracle\n"
      "&prompt.user;cat &gt;&gt; ~oracle/.bash_profile &lt;&lt; EOF\n"
      "ulimit -n 63536\n"
      "EOF"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: user_management.xml:843
#, no-c-format
msgid "Displaying login banners"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: user_management.xml:845
#, no-c-format
msgid "It is often necessary to place a banner on login screens on all servers for legal/audit policy reasons or to give security instructions to users."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: user_management.xml:851
#, no-c-format
msgid "To print a login banner <emphasis>after</emphasis> a user logs in on a text based terminal, for example, using SSH or on a local console, you can use the file <filename>/etc/motd</filename> (motd = message of the day). The file exists by default on &productname;, but it is empty. Simply add content to the file that is applicable/required by the organization."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: user_management.xml:861
#, no-c-format
msgid "Banner length"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: user_management.xml:862
#, no-c-format
msgid "Try to keep the login banner content to a single terminal page (or less), as it scrolls the screen if it does not fit, making it more difficult to read."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: user_management.xml:869
#, no-c-format
msgid "You can also have a login banner printed <emphasis>before</emphasis> a user logs in on a text based terminal. For local console logins, you can edit the <filename>/etc/issue</filename> file, which causes the banner to be displayed before the login prompt. For logins via SSH, you can edit the <quote>Banner</quote> parameter in the <filename>/etc/ssh/sshd_config</filename> file, which then appropriately displays the banner text before the SSH login prompt."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: user_management.xml:879
#, no-c-format
msgid "For graphical logins via GDM, you can follow <link xlink:href=\"https://help.gnome.org/admin/system-admin-guide/stable/login-banner.html.en\"> the GNOME admin guide</link> to set up a login banner. Furthermore, you can make the following changes to require a user to acknowledge the legal banner by selecting <guimenu>Yes</guimenu> or <guimenu>No</guimenu> . Edit the <filename>/etc/gdm/Xsession</filename> file and add the following lines at the <emphasis>beginning</emphasis> of the script:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: user_management.xml:889
#, no-c-format
msgid "if ! /usr/bin/gdialog --yesno '\\n<replaceable>This system is classified...</replaceable>\\n' 10 10; then\n"
      "    /usr/bin/gdialog --infobox 'Aborting login'\n"
      "    exit 1;\n"
      "fi"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: user_management.xml:894
#, no-c-format
msgid "The text <replaceable>This system is classified...</replaceable> needs to be replaced with the desired banner text. This dialog does not prevent a login from progressing. For more information about GDM scripting, refer to the <link xlink:href=\"https://help.gnome.org/admin/gdm/stable/configuration.html.en#scripting\"> GDM Admin Manual</link> ."
msgstr ""

